Correlation Matrix - Bivariate Analysis

library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)

# Assuming 'cleaned_zirconia_df' is your data frame and has been properly cleaned.
# Make sure to use the correct data frame name as 'cleaned_zirconia_df'.

# Subset the dataframe to include only numeric columns
numeric_df <- cleaned_zirconia_df[sapply(cleaned_zirconia_df, is.numeric)]

# Calculate the correlation matrix
cor_mat <- cor(numeric_df)

# Melt the correlation matrix for plotting
cor_melted <- melt(cor_mat)

# Plot the heatmap with a cleaner theme
ggplot(cor_melted, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1,1), space = "Lab", name="Correlation") +
  labs(title = "Correlation Heatmap of Zirconia Dataset", x = "", y = "") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1, size = 10, color = "grey20"),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10, color = "grey20"),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10)
  ) +
  coord_fixed()

Visualizing the Lm model

**(ii) Random forest Classifier*

# Omit rows with missing values
train_data <- na.omit(train_data)
test_data <- na.omit(test_data)


# Fit Random Forest Model
rf_model <- randomForest(price ~ ., data = train_data, ntree = 100)  # ntree can be adjusted based on computational resources

# Predict on test data
rf_predictions <- predict(rf_model, newdata = test_data)

# Calculate RMSE for Random Forest
rf_rmse <- sqrt(mean((test_data$price - rf_predictions)^2))
print(paste("RMSE for Random Forest:", rf_rmse))
## [1] "RMSE for Random Forest: 648.151082385619"

# Ensure that 'price' is not included in the character columns
char_cols <- sapply(train_data[, -ncol(train_data)], is.character)
factor_cols <- sapply(train_data[, -ncol(train_data)], is.factor)

# If character or factor columns are present, one-hot encode them
if (any(char_cols) | any(factor_cols)) {
  # Combine character and factor columns
  to_encode_cols <- char_cols | factor_cols
  # Use dummyVars to one-hot encode them
  dummies <- dummyVars("~ .", data = train_data[, to_encode_cols])
  train_data_transformed <- predict(dummies, newdata = train_data)
  test_data_transformed <- predict(dummies, newdata = test_data)

  # Bind the transformed columns with the rest of the data
  train_data_final <- cbind(train_data_transformed, train_data[, !to_encode_cols])
  test_data_final <- cbind(test_data_transformed, test_data[, !to_encode_cols])
} else {
  # If no character or factor columns are present, use the data directly
  train_data_final <- train_data
  test_data_final <- test_data
}

# Convert to matrices, ensuring 'price' is the last column
xgb_train <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(train_data_final[, -ncol(train_data_final)]), label = train_data_final$price)
xgb_test <- xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(test_data_final[, -ncol(test_data_final)]))

# Now proceed with XGBoost training
params <- list(
  objective = "reg:squarederror",
  eta = 0.3,
  max_depth = 6
)
xgb_model <- xgboost(params = params, data = xgb_train, nrounds = 100, verbose = 0)

# Predicting
xgb_predictions <- predict(xgb_model, newdata = xgb_test)

# Remember to add error handling and data validation as necessary.
# Print all predictions
head(xgb_predictions)
## [1]   722.4116   743.1815  1678.7468 11247.0488  1785.1075   597.2286

Summary for XGBoost Model

# Calculate RMSE
rmse <- sqrt(mean((test_data$price - xgb_predictions)^2))

# Calculate MAE
mae <- mean(abs(test_data$price - xgb_predictions))

# R-squared calculation
ss_res <- sum((test_data$price - xgb_predictions)^2)
ss_tot <- sum((test_data$price - mean(test_data$price))^2)
r_squared <- 1 - (ss_res / ss_tot)

# Print the metrics
print(paste("RMSE:", rmse))
## [1] "RMSE: 565.503578566408"
print(paste("MAE:", mae))
## [1] "MAE: 293.855693735697"
print(paste("R-squared:", r_squared))
## [1] "R-squared: 0.979766771001865"
